Section.Description: A series of checks related to linked and imported files in the model.

Check.CheckName: Reference Types for Linked Revit Files (Overlay vs. Attachement)
Check.Description: COUNT and LIST of the link method (overlay vs. attach) for each Revit link in the model. Revit links reference type should be set to "Overlay" unless it is needed to be set to "Attachment"

Check.CheckName: Linked Revit Files are Pinned in Place
Check.Description: PASS/FAIL check to determine if any linked Revit files are not pinned in place. Will Fail if any are found.
Check.FailureMessage: There are linked Revit models that are not pinned in place.

Check.Description: Checks if the URS File is Linked
Check.FailureMessage: URS File is not Linked

Check.CheckName: Architectural and Structural Linked Revit Files Are Room Bounding
Check.Description: PASS/FAIL check to determine if any linked Revit files are not room bounding. Will Fail if any are found.
Check.FailureMessage: There are linked Revit models that are not room bounding

Check.Description: COUNT and LIST all linked CAD files in the model.
Check.FailureMessage: No CAD files should be linked in the model

Check.CheckName: Linked and/or Imported CAD Files are Not Visible in All Views

Check.FailureMessage: Linked and/or imported CAD files should be set to current view only unless when necessary

Section.Description: A series of checks related to worksets in the model.

Check.Description: COUNT and LIST of all user worksets for a Revit model or indicates '*Not Workshared*' if worksharing is not enabled.

Check.CheckName: Wrong Elements on "Shared Levels and Grids" Workset
Check.Description: COUNT and LIST of all elements in the model that are on the 'Shared Levels and Grids' workset that are not levels or grids. Note that the 'Shared Levels and Grids' workset must have both 'level' and 'grid' (case insensitive) in the name in order to be recognized.

Check.CheckName: Levels and Grids are placed on "Shared Levels and Grids" Workset
Check.Description: PASS/FAIL check to determine if any levels or grids are not placed on the "Shared Levels and Grids" workset. Will Fail if any are found.
Check.FailureMessage: Not all levels and/or grids are placed on the "Shared Levels and Grids" workset

Check.CheckName: Linked Models are Assigned to their Proper Workset
Check.Description: Checking if Revit Linked Files are assigned to their proper Workset
Check.FailureMessage: Not all Revit Linked Files are assigned to their proper workset

Check.CheckName: Linked and/or Imported CAD Files are Placed in their Proper Workset
Check.Description: Checking if all linked and/or imported CAD files in the model that are visible in all views are placed in their proper workset. Note: CAD files should be set to current view only unless needed otherwise.
Check.FailureMessage: Not all linked and/or imported CAD files in the model that are visible in all views are placed in their proper workset. Note: CAD files should be set to current view only unless needed otherwise.

Check.CheckName: Scope Boxes are placed on "Scope Boxes" Workset
Check.Description: Checking if all scope boxes are placed on the "Scope Boxes" workset.
Check.FailureMessage: Not all scope boxes are placed on the "Scope Boxes" workset.

Section.Description: A series of checks related to project browser organization

Check.Description: COUNT of all views in the model. Views typically do not impact model size, but too many unmanaged views can impact user efficiency.
COUNT of all schedules in the model. Schedules typically do not impact model size, but too many unmanaged views can impact user efficiency.
COUNT and LIST of all legend views in the model.
COUNT of all sheets in the model. Sheets typically do not impact model size, but too many unmanaged views can impact user efficiency.
COUNT of all placeholder sheets in the model.
COUNT and LIST of all the scope boxes used in the model
COUNT and LIST of all view templates in the model.
COUNT of all views that have no View Templates assigned to them in the model. This may be indicative of unneeded working views that can be removed from a model.
COUNT and LIST of all views (not including views that can be placed on more than one sheet, like Schedules and Legends) that are not placed on a sheet in the model.
Returns Views that have no assigned "Folder" or wrongly assigned. Views should be under Working or Documentation, or Coordination or Analytical.
Check.FailureMessage: Not all views have assigned "Folder" or wrongly assigned. Views should be under Working or Documentation, or Coordination or Analytical.

Check.Description: Returns Views that have no assigned Sub-Discipline or Department
Check.FailureMessage: Not all views have assigned Sub-Discipline or Department

Check.CheckName: Navisworks Export View Exists in the Model with Template Assigned
Check.Description: PASS/FAIL check to determine if there is a 3D view named "3D-Navisworks-Export" for export to Navisworks and has assigned View Template and placed under "Coordination" Folder
Check.FailureMessage: There is no 3D view named "3D-Navisworks-Export" for export to Navisworks and/or Navisworks view has no View Template assigned and/or not placed under "Coordination" Folder

Check.CheckName: Documentation Views have View Templates Assigned
Check.Description: Checking if documentation views have View Templates assigned to them
Check.FailureMessage: Not all documentation views have View Templates assigned to them

Check.CheckName: Views On Sheets With No View Template
Check.Description: Checking if all views on sheets that have no view templates assigned to them in the model. Printed views with no view template may be indicative of poorly managed or followed standards in the model, which can lead to less efficient methods of control element appearance.
Check.FailureMessage: Not all views on sheets have view templates assigned to them in the model

Section.Description: A series of checks related to model elements in the model.

Check.Description: Checking if in-place family elements exist in the model.
Check.FailureMessage: In-place family elements exist in the model. In-place families should not be used. Families should be system or loadable families.

Check.Description: Checking if generic model families exist in the model.
Check.FailureMessage: Generic model families exist in the model. Generic model families should not be used. Families should be categorized, and if generic models are to be used, they should be sub-categorized.

Check.Description: PASS/FAIL check to determine if there are any modeled elements that are duplicates (identical elements at the same location and base level). Check will Fail if any duplicate element is found. **WARNING** Running this check can take a significant amount of time to complete.
Check.FailureMessage: Element is a duplicate at the same location and base level.

Check.Description: PASS/FAIL check to determine if there are any mirrored instances of loadable components. Check will fail if any element is mirrored
Check.FailureMessage: The following elements have been mirrored

Check.Description: COUNT and LIST of all elements in each phase of the model.

Section.Description: Checks in this section help monitor the result of actions taken over the course of a model’s development, which can directly impact the model’s performance. Proper management of these items can improve model performance.

Check.Description: File size for reported Revit model should not exceed 200 MB (megabytes).
COUNT of all warnings in the model. Too many unresolved warnings can cause performance issues in a Revit model.

COUNT of all elements that can be purged from a Revit model. A large number of unneeded elements can increase the model size with no benefit. Note that the count reported here may differ from the Purge Unused command in the Revit interface due to API restraints.
COUNT of all model group elements in the model. Too many model groups can be an indication of improper modeling techniques.
